{"copyright": {"licenseType": "NO", "determinationType": "OTHER", "thirdPartyContentCondition": "NOT_SET"}, "subjectCategories": ["COMPUTER OPERATIONS AND HARDWARE"], "exportControl": {"isExportControl": "NO", "ear": "NO", "itar": "NO"}, "created": "2013-08-09T17:58:00.0000000+00:00", "distributionDate": "2019-07-12T00:00:00.0000000+00:00", "center": {"code": "CDMS", "name": "Legacy CDMS", "id": "092d6e0881874968859b972d39a888dc"}, "onlyAbstract": false, "sensitiveInformation": 2, "abstract": "This paper has five purposes. First, to focus upon the key relationships that bound the technology choices for large, archival, digital storage devices; second, to identify the motivations for selecting the optical technology for a petabit-exabit level storage system (10 to the 15th to 10 to the 18th bits); third, to present a generic example and a specific implementation of a terabit-level optical storage device; fourth, to characterize the global design space constraints that will allow one to build a technology-limited optical store; and fifth, to sketch the outline of the BYTERON concept, a wideband 10 to the 16th to 10 to the 17th bit optical store concept and contrast its performance to that of an optical store that is in operation today", "title": "Wideband optical storage", "stiType": "CONFERENCE_PROCEEDINGS", "distribution": "PUBLIC", "submittedDate": "2013-08-09T17:58:00.0000000+00:00", "isLessonsLearned": false, "authorAffiliations": [{"sequence": 0, "submissionId": 19790040224, "meta": {"author": {"name": "Heard, H. G."}, "organization": {"name": "Institute for Advanced Computation", "location": "Moffett Field, Calif., United States"}}, "id": "6adc98b8cfe047b68fffac1bb87543dc"}], "disseminated": "METADATA_ONLY", "stiTypeDetails": "Conference Proceedings", "technicalReviewType": "TECHNICAL_REVIEW_TYPE_NONE", "modified": "2011-08-16T00:00:00.0000000+00:00", "meetings": [{"submissionId": 19790040224, "sponsors": [{"meta": {"organization": {"name": "Astronautic"}}, "me